<br>
Zatdatine thought about this as she sat in Fish's Ale sipping a Honey Mead in the moist heat of a summer night. Trumpy Irontoe, Fish's resident Dwarf, leered.  <br>
<br>
&quot;I had to make a choice,&quot; she said, &quot;and my choice was to align myself with the Ring of Scale--the Dragons. Otherwise, if I would have completed quests for the League of Antonican Bards and aligned myself with them, my standing in the Ring of Scale would have <br>
been lowered instead of increased!  Why, Veeshan?&quot;  <br>
<br>
&quot;Look who's here!&quot; called out Trumpy, whose breath smelled like too many Short Beers.  &quot;The bastard child!&quot; <br>
<br>
Zatdatine's head whirled around, her neck as taut as a Ranger's bowstring.  &quot;What was that?!&quot; she whispered.<br>
<br>
&quot;The bastard child!&quot; grinned Trumpy.  &quot;She's half-Human,<br>
half-Elf!  She can't tell whether she's one or the other!&quot; <br>
<br>
Zatdatine quickly jumped off her barstool, knocking it over with a wooden clatter, and placed her magical dagger, a Dragoon Dirk, to the rude Dwarf's neck.  <br>
<br>
&quot;I'll have you know,&quot; she hissed, &quot;that my mother and<br>
father were married before they had me, and as for knowing whether I'm Human or Elf, I am both, so shove<br>
off, you dirty old Dwarf!&quot;  Her turquoise eyes blazed.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Sheez!&quot; cried Trumpy, his eyes wide with fear and awe, rubbing his neck.  &quot;Can't you take a joke, Zat-dat-een?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;It's Zat-a-tine,&quot; the platinum-haired Bard replied.  &quot;The D is silent.  Now, leave me in peace, or I shall have to call upon the might of the Dragon Queen to strike you!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You're interested in dragons, eh, girl?&quot; asked Trumpy slyly. &quot;Go into the catacombs and tell S'ragg Bloodheart hello for me!&quot; He took another gluttonous swig of his ale.<br>
<br>
&quot;Are you trying to get me killed?&quot; Zatdatine was furious. <br>
&quot;You know I can't go into the catacombs, and especially to where S'ragg Bloodheart lives, without worshipping Bertoxxulous!  I worship Veeshan, who is neutral, and<br>
I'm on a quest to find out as much information as I can about the Mother of all Wurms.  S'ragg won't help me!&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;If you wanna know a dragon personally,&quot; grumbled Trumpy, &quot;then go get eaten!  Night, night!&quot;  He belched.<br>
<br>
Zatdatine exited the tavern into the summer's heat, not knowing what to do next.  &quot;Should I go now?&quot; she asked herself.  &quot;Should I leave Qeynos?  Where should I start on my dream, this ultimate Dragon Quest of mine?&quot;   <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kreeden>Kreeden</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.badassbuddy.com/images/buddies/badassbuddy_com-hydros.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/15/03 10:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1008.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Dragonquest</span><hr size=1> The completely shrouded figure towards the left side stirred a bit at the mention of the half-elven remarks, and watched with hidden eyes as the young bard, or so he was pretty sure of, explained her story of her choices she has very dramatically made.  Zatdatine seemed approximately the same season as Kreeden. <br>
<br>
Kreeden arrived in Qeynos earlier in the night, and carefully made his way into the Fish's Ale, picking an isolated area to make himself comfortable.  Zatdatine's commotion stirred Kreeden from his resting state, which was a half squating half standing position against the wall.<br>
<br>
Her arguments with the short-excuse-for-a-bartender reminded Kreeden of his own struggles for equality, in a world where his brethern, and the art he practices is so frowned upon.<br>
<br>
Why Kreeden did what he did next still baffles him, a momentary flaw of character, lack of appetite, a mental lapse, he still is not sure.  As Zatdatine went out the door, Kreeden's reptilian eyes flashed at everyone in the room from beneath the heavy shrouded veil and robes he enclosed himself in.  As Kreeden in one fluid motion stood and took a step forward, Trumpy eyed him and excalimed, &quot; 'Ey!  There be a lizzy among us! &quot;.  Kreeden ran quickly out the door, and gathered shadows around him to hide himself.  Zatdatine was walking ahead, and stopped when she heard Trumpy's far to loud and intrusive voice.  Kreeden, concealed, crept up to Zatdatine, and whispered close to her ear,<br>
<br>
&quot;I am with you.  Let us go on your quessst.  Be aware I am not accccepted here, and though in every way different, our overall ssstruggle is very much the sssame.  Lead, I will follow.&quot; <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=rhaxalygen>Rhaxalygen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 251<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/16/03 2:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1008.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Starting the Journey</span><hr size=1> Zatdatine appraised the shrouded figure. Iksar, no doubt.<br>
His reptilian eyes were hidden now, and only the dark robe surrounding his scales was all she could see. <br>
Well. Iksar were not frequent visitors to the city of Qeynos, as Antonius Bayle was opposed to all things <br>
evil--and all creatures evil.  Zatdatine supposed, through the shadows, that Kreeden was a Necromancer. <br>
<br>
Suddenly, she noticed Guard Beren, one of the good Guards of Qeynos, untainted by corruption, glance <br>
their way.  &quot;Keep walking,&quot; she whispered, &quot;as if you<br>
haven't noticed anything.  We'll head for the nearest<br>
exit to North Qeynos, and then toward the city gates!&quot; <br>
<br>
Kreeden nodded, and the two figures crept their way through the darkened city streets.  Noticing that the guards were very suspicious of the shrouded figure, Zatdatine drummed a chorus of Selo's Accelerando to<br>
speed their way through the city and past the gate. <br>
<br>
&quot;There!&quot; she whispered when the two were safely in<br>
the outer regions of Qeynos Hills, past the eyesight<br>
of the watchful kill-stealer Guard Nash.  &quot;That was<br>
easy!  Not too difficult for you, I suppose?&quot; she asked<br>
the Iksar, who was panting a little from the great rush of <br>
speed that her percussion song had provided.   <br>
<br>
Zatdatine sat down.  &quot;No one can see us here,&quot; she<br>
told the figure, &quot;at least not any guards.  Near the <br>
gnoll-caves of Blackburrow, there is a wooden shelter where we can camp.  I'm rather tired; how about you?&quot;  <br>
Her eyes were kind, even though Kreeden was of a <br>
race of creatures that she was supposed to slaughter. <br>
<br>
She led Kreeden to the shelter of which she spoke, <br>
a meager wooden box-like room with only a campfire<br>
by it.  Within, she told the shrouded Iksar her story. <br>
<br>
&quot;My name is Zatdatine, and I'm a Bard.  I also serve<br>
Veeshan, known as the Wyrmqueen, because in all my<br>
days of experience, I've never known or heard of a life<br>
form more powerful than the Dragons.  Maybe save thee!&quot;<br>
She laughedsoftly, and continued.  &quot;I love the wurms!&quot;   <br>
<br>
&quot;I've lived all my life here in Qeynos, and all my life, I've known prejudice because I'm not completely Human or<br>
completely Elven.  Pure-bloods are Norrath's standard<br>
population, whether they be Ogre or Human or Troll!  I<br>
am one of the only creatures that be of mixed race.  <br>
Humans regard me as weak because of my Elven blood, and Elves regard me as tainted because they regard THEIR blood as not only pure, but superior to Man's.&quot; <br>
<br>
She watched as the figure nodded, the hood of his shroud bobbing up and down.  &quot;What is your name and<br>
history, O Iksar?&quot;  She glanced around for gnolls. None. <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kreeden>Kreeden</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.badassbuddy.com/images/buddies/badassbuddy_com-hydros.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/16/03 9:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1008.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> A History</span><hr size=1> Kreeden seemed slightly more inclined to conversation now then he had been at the Fish's Ale.  The iskar were a race not known for conversation with other races other than battlecries.  However, somewhere deep down in his scaly skin, Kreeden felt a connection with the chipper half-elf.<br>
<br>
Kreeden removed his shroud, his distinctly figured reptilian face exposed and his eyes flickering a flux of dark green and pale red's.<br>
<br>
&quot;I am from Cabilis, as are all others of my race.  However, Kunark soon began to bore me.  The lore there was not interesting to me as it is my own lore.  I'm sure you feel much the same way about your home city, wherever you may have came from.  I grew dissatisified with life on Kunark, and I gathered some books of lore of Antionican cities, and the cities of Faydwer, and even the mystical isle of Odus.  These interested me very much, the candle in my room was lit well into the night, as I hovered over these pieces of literature, fanciful stories of mighty dwarves, cities in trees, strongholds of orcs and gnolls.  All so unreal to me.  One night I was reading of a brave barbarian warrior, in search of a mystical polar bear in the icy tundra of permafrost, when I fell asleep.&quot;  Kreeden paused and gathered his thoughts as Zatdatine looked on and slowly nodded.<br>
<br>
&quot;My master discovered me there, late for class, face buried in a book titled &quot;History of Halas Vol. XIV.&quot;  Of course, this did not fare well.  Usually crimes such as this were to be punsihed by death, however my father holds high position in the regiment of Cabilis, so it was decided for me to be exiled.  I was sent out of the city, into the backyard I once called home, now called hell.  I made my way to Firiona Vie, very carefully, as that settlement would not tolerate my appearence by any standards.  I cloaked myself in shadows as I approached the city, and I made my way to the docks as a ship came into view, luckily I attracted no attention and made it safely to the ship.  There I found an empty storage area and I drifted to sleep.&quot;  <br>
<br>
Kreeden looked rather pensive for a moment, then managed a frown and said, with a hint of regret, &quot;I fear this story has rambled on to long.&quot;<br>
<br>
Zatdatine's brows narrowed, &quot;What do you mean?  Can't you tell of how you came to Fish's Ale?&quot;<br>
<br>
Kreeden quickly said, &quot;I'm a necromancer, yet I shun from pure hate.  Hate is an uncontrollable part of everyone that should not be provoked.  If you must know I was discovered by a ship-hand whom clubbed me with an empty barrel.  I killed him.&quot;<br>
<br>
Zatdatine moved back a bit, processing what she just heard.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, I killed him, it was self defence.  I am no murderer.  There was no land in sight, as I peeked from around the corner of where I'd just slaughtered a man.  from behind me I heard mumblings, I turned and upon a tier above me there was a militia of three of four wizards, seemed to be humans but I couldn't tell, my eyes were not well-adjusted to the light yet and the sun was directly behind them.  They were gathering mana and directing it at me.&quot;<br>
<br>
Zatdatine leaned a little closer, with mounting interest.<br>
<br>
&quot;I am no powerful necromancer.  I have had only basic instruction and knew I was no match for this team of wizards.  I grabbed my dagger and with a quick slice was able to cut a taunt rope behind me, bringing a sail down between me and the wizards, just as their mana reached full capacity.  I dove into the water, being an excellent swimmer, swam a solid fifty or so yards from the ship before surfacing.  The ship was quickly falling apart, the sails on fire and falling, I watched the ship shrink into the distance, and then realized that I was in the middle of nowhere, with only a waterlogged map to guide me.  I floated helplessly for a while, turning over different options in my head, deciding that gating back to Cabilis was not a good option and that swimming in any direction continiously will only get me exhausted.  I had learned in my studies that there is a current in the seas around Antonica, a circular one.  Thusly, I swam in the direction the ship had dissappeared.  I came across some driftwood, climbed onto it, and rested.  I stayed on the wood for at least 6 sunrises.  Often I swam, pushing my make-shift raft, only to get my skin wet so the sun may dry it out again.  Eventually, I came across Qeyons.  I climbed ashore, and rested.  The rest you know.&quot;<br>
<br>
Zatdatine nodded thoughtfully.<br>
<br>
&quot;I get long winded at times, I apologize&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;No proble-&quot;  Zatdatine stopped midsentance &quot;- What's that sound?&quot;<br>
<br>
Kreeden and Zatdatine stopped and turned their attention towards the one door of the wooden hut. Hurried footsteps, many feet. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=rhaxalygen>Rhaxalygen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 252<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/17/03 11:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1008.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> You'd better STOP--HEY!  What's that sound?  Rangers! </span><hr size=1> Kreeden and Zatdatine crouched inside the wooden room, trying to hide themselves from whatever or <br>
whomever the footsteps might belong to. They both<br>
listened, hearing a conversation not meant for any<br>
ears--save the good guards of Qeynos and the <br>
servants of Tunare and Karana in Surefall Glade! <br>
<br>
&quot;Good rangers,&quot; they heard a deep voice rumble, <br>
presumably a guard's (maybe Guard Bixby?), &quot;it<br>
seems to us that there is a Necromancer, an Iksar,<br>
running wild about these lands, and we need your<br>
help to track him--or her!--down and slaughter him!&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Good heavens!&quot; cried Holly Windstalker, a level 33<br>
Human Ranger, a Protector of the Pine.  &quot;I'll certainly<br>
do as much as I can, and if I find this lizard, I'll slice<br>
him to ribbons!  Natural selection at work, I always say,<br>
especially for an Iksar!  Servant of Thule!  Bah!&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;I'll also set myself to the task,&quot; said the Half-Elven<br>
Apprentice of Saxuus, who so far had taken to running<br>
along the Qeynos Hills path with nary a how-do-ye-do.<br>
&quot;It is my duty to keep the path along Qeynos Hills safe,<br>
and if I run across this vile Iksar, I'll kill him, too!&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Good,&quot; said Guard Bixby as Guard Nash nodded also.<br>
&quot;The lizard seems to be travelling with a girl, a Half-<br>
Elven Bard with hair the color of platinum, and if you<br>
see her, bring her in for questioning.  Consorting with<br>
an Iksar is punishable by death under Qeynos law!&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Will do,&quot; said the Apprentice of Saxuus, speeding away.<br>
<br>
Zatdatine's blood temperature rose about 50 degrees. <br>
&quot;They're looking to kill!&quot; she whispered fearfully, &quot;and<br>
I suggest we risk attack by the gnolls and go through<br>
Blackburrow into the wilds of Everfrost.  There, we <br>
can at least escape for some time, and then when<br>
the danger is past, we can go back through the<br>
gnoll-caves and head for the Western Plains of Karana.<br>
I've heard of drakes in Ak-Anon, but that's a long way<br>
off!&quot;  The Bard waited anxiously to hear Kreeden's reply. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kreeden>Kreeden</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.badassbuddy.com/images/buddies/badassbuddy_com-hydros.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/17/03 5:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1008.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Into Blackburrow</span><hr size=1> Kreeden only sighed, a rather lax reaction to just hearing his own death sentance told a few mere feet away.  Being hunted for no reason at all is what he expected, coming to a land where the lizards are not welcome for some reason.  Kreeden nodded at Zatdatine's propsal that they head to Blackburrow.<br>
<br>
Waiting a few moments, Zatdatine poked her head from the shelter to make sure the coast is clear.  Kreeden gathered shadows about him and followed Zatdatine, running towards a cave-like opening, dubiously carved into the shape of a gnoll, or so Kreeden guessed, from the illustrations of books he'd read.  Kreeden had never seen a gnoll, not that he had a burning desire to, but the thought crossed his mind as he blindly followed a young, yet brave, bard into the lair of them.  However, from around the corner of the opening lept a gnoll with a very large, rusted over scythe.  <br>
<br>
&quot;Gnoll!&quot;  Kreeden said in an urgent whisper, loud enough for Zatdatine to hear, yet hushed from ears that may be nearby.<br>
<br>
&quot;Not here!  Take it inside!  Can't let people see you!&quot;<br>
<br>
Kreeden was positive the gnoll couldn't see him however he feared for his comrade's safety.  Yes, care isn't something expected from his kind, however without Zatdatine he is lost in an unknown land whever everyone wants to kill him.  No, Kreeden liked his allies at the moment.  Kreeden followed Zatdatine inside the cave, into a narrow rather worn hallway.  safely around the corner, she waited for the gnoll to come around the corner.  Very quickly, she drew her Dragoon Dirk and placed it squarely in the right side of the gnoll.  He was hurt, but not dead, as he reared back and took a mighty swipe at Zatdatine's head.  He stopped, almost connecting with Zatdatine's head, and was surrounded by green transparent bubbles, they dispersed from his body and floated to the now revealed black hooded figure standing behind Zatdatine.  The gnoll staggered wildly, stunned not only at the lizard he was facing and the blakc magics that had just been evoked on him.  Zatdatine placed a firm finishing blow with her dirk in the collarbone of the gnoll.  <br>
<br>
&quot;I heard they were alot tougher in the books..&quot;  Kreeden said, managing a twisted grin visible beneath his veil.<br>
<br>
&quot;Aye, they are, that was a runt my friend.&quot;Zatdatine said grimly.<br>
<br>
The grin faded somewhat as Kreeden mentally prepareed himself for gnolls taller then him and very burly looking.  <br>
<br>
The two rested for a moment, Kreeden hiding in the corner and Zatdatine humming a soothing song.  Kreeden broke the silence, &quot;So, do you know your way around in here?&quot;<br>
<br>
Zatdatine replied, &quot;I believe so, it should be a straight shot through, but I don't know what kind of opposition we might face.  When we leave this hallway it opens up into a vast area, bathed in sunlight, there is so many tunnels here that it will be very easy to get lost, so stay very close and remain hidden unless we're in serious trouble.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kreeden nodded, Zatdatine stowed her lute in her backpack, slid her dirk into her boot and they moved towards the exit of the hallway, Kreeden cloaked as always. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=rhaxalygen>Rhaxalygen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 253<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/17/03 9:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1008.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> The Wild Creatures of Everfrost</span><hr size=1> Zatdatine and Kreeden wound their way through the<br>
empty tunnels of Blackburrow, helped by their clear<br>
Infravision in the darkest places.  Eventually, they<br>
emerged into a snow-white landscape, the atmosphere<br>
fogged with a flurry of snowflakes. <br>
<br>
&quot;This is Everfrost,&quot; said Zatdatine.  &quot;As long as we<br>
stick around here, and not wander too far out where<br>
the ice giants can get us, then we should be able to<br>
sneak back into Blackburrow and through Qeynos<br>
Hills to the Western Plains of Karana very shortly.&quot; <br>
<br>
Kreeden pulled his dark shroud more closely around<br>
him, and Zatdatine sang her Elemental Rhythms, <br>
learned in her ninth season, protecting them both<br>
from the hazards of heat and cold.  The two explored.<br>
<br>
As Zatdatine expected, they encountered white wolves,<br>
gnoll pups, woolly spiders, snow orc troopers, ice goblin<br>
scouts and whelps, and other aggressive creatures.  However, none of them dared attack them, for Kreeden<br>
and Zatdatine were both far above them in seasons.  Instead, the wildlife watched them warily, unharmed. <br>
<br>
Suddenly, in the midst of their explorations, they heard<br>
a tiny voice:  &quot;Ugly creature near my feet, methinks you'd be good to eat!&quot;  It was an ice goblin whelp, no<br>
doubt, but THIS young goblin, unlike its fellows, was <br>
a bright shade of GREEN.  Green, like Tunare's leaves!<br>
<br>
&quot;Excuse me,&quot; Zatdatine said haughtily, &quot;but I don't think<br>
you'd want to eat us!  The Iksar and I are both well above<br>
you in levels, and as for the taste of us, well, we taste<br>
stringy and bland!&quot;  The green goblin laughed, showing<br>
his tiny and yet very sharp teeth.  He doubled over. <br>
<br>
&quot;Dragons are the thing you seek.  Climb on up to <br>
Veeshan's Peak!  If you're too low-level to take this<br>
advice, then head off to Kelethin!  That place is nice!&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Kelethin has forest drakelings, for sure,&quot; said the Bard,<br>
&quot;but if I venture there, then the Fier'Dal militia, the Emerald Warriors, will slaughter my Iksar companion!&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Iksar bad and Iksar mean,&quot; rhymed the green goblin. <br>
&quot;Kill him with songs, Zatdatine!&quot;  The Bard gasped! <br>
<br>
&quot;How did you know my name?&quot; she asked.  &quot;And, for<br>
that matter, how in the world did you know that I sought<br>
the dragons?  Are you psychic or what, green whelp?&quot; <br>
<br>
The young goblin grinned.  &quot;I eat Trolls!&quot; he exclaimed.   <br>
<br>
Zatdatine looked to the Iksar.  Clearly, this creature was weird, as in W-E-I-R-D, and yet she didn't know what<br>
to do next. <br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kreeden>Kreeden</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.badassbuddy.com/images/buddies/badassbuddy_com-hydros.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/17/03 10:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1008.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> A Fork of Fate</span><hr size=1> Kreeden had a look of intrigue in his eyes, &quot;I've read of these creatures, these seers.  Through mysterious potions and mystical chantings they are about to prophesie unusual events.  I'm sure that an iskar in the lands of everfrost is quite an unusual sight, muchless traveling in peaceful terms with a half-elven bard.  How he gathered such in-depth information about you is beyond me.&quot;<br>
<br>
Zatdatine simply nodded, still accepting the fact that a goblin had just told her of her own intentions, likely not hearing a word that Kreeden had just spoke.<br>
<br>
Kreeden thoughtfully reproached the situation.  His intelligence was well above any normal iskar.  &quot;It's also possible that whom we talked to was not a goblin at all..  could be a shapeshifter of any sort, a form of a diety, anything really.  Claiming to eat trolls is a large statement for someone with such small stature.&quot;  Kreeden's eyes shifted and pale green strands of color swirled within.  It's definately something to think upon.  I am for whatever you decide, Zatdatine, I am simply here for adventure.  Veeshan's Peak sounds very dangerous, and I know not of the location, however Kelethin is far off I believe, and though I am entirely disliked upon that continent ('as on all continents' Kreeden added silently to himself), I would enjoy seeing the tree villages and witnessing the lore I have only dreamed about.&quot;<br>
<br>
Zatdatine looked rather puzzled, and weary.<br>
<br>
&quot;We should head back to our origional camp, you don't look so good, sleep on it and let me know what you want to do in the morning.&quot;  Kreeden said, extending a helping, albeit scaly, hand to Zatdatine to steady her on the slippery slopes. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=rhaxalygen>Rhaxalygen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 254<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/18/03 2:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1008.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> A Choice and a Consequence</span><hr size=1> Zatdatine was pleasantly surprised as Kreeden, the<br>
necromantic Iksar, extended his hand to help her down<br>
the icy slopes of Everfrost. Secretly, she had always<br>
wanted to touch an Iksar, but deep down, she knew <br>
that this would likely be impossible.  No other Lizardman<br>
would want to touch palms with a Half-Elven Bard except<br>
to capture, or maybe to Harm Touch, them.  Now, her dream had come true!  She was grateful for Kreeden's <br>
assistance, and amazed that one of his kind WAS kind!  <br>
<br>
&quot;Wait, wait, wait, wait, wait, wait!&quot; called a tiny voice.  The green goblin whelp stumbled down the slopes after<br>
Kreeden and Zatdatine, barely keeping his balance. &quot;I<br>
sense you want to go to Kelethin, the home of the <br>
Wood Elves.  Would you like some assistance in<br>
getting there?&quot;  He grinned his gleeful, sharp-toothed grin and spread his arms out wide, as if greeting them. <br>
<br>
&quot;Yes,&quot; replied Zatdatine warily, since she did not fully<br>
trust this goblin, &quot;but maybe tomorrow.  The Iksar and<br>
I want to return to our camp outside Blackburrow to rest,<br>
and perhaps when morning comes, we shall seek you<br>
out.&quot;  She gazed into the goblin's black, beady eyes. <br>
As it was, she could not read his motives.  What then?<br>
<br>
&quot;Go, go!&quot; said the goblin.  &quot;Rest, rest!  But remember, <br>
that tomorrow morning, you two face a choice and a<br>
consequence. Both are of the utmost importance!&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;A choice and a consequence?&quot; asked Kreeden.  &quot;What<br>
might those two things be, goblin whelp?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Tomorrow, tomorrow!&quot; cried the creature.  &quot;Sleep on it!&quot; <br>
<br>
So they did.  The Half Elf and the Iksar nestled down <br>
inside the wooden room nearest Blackburrow to sleep<br>
as the campfire blazed.  The Bard thought that the <br>
fire must be enchanted, or something like that, because<br>
it never burned out or consumed any of its wooden fuel. <br>
<br>
The next morning, they were faced with nothing but a<br>
few watching gnolls.  The camp looked deserted, <br>
although within a few hours, swarms of adventurers<br>
would be heading for the caves, trying to kill lots of <br>
gnolls and win faction with Qeynos.  Suddenly, a <br>
white light appeared in the purplish-red eastern sky...<br>
<br>
&quot;That's the sun,&quot; said Zatdatine, but as she looked closer, and her eyes widened to the size of dinner <br>
plates, Kreeden hissed, &quot;That's not the sun!&quot; <br>
<br>
The bright light seemed to engulf them.  Was their choice either to run or to flee?  The two did not know. <br>
And what was the consequence?  Still a mystery! <br>
