by this new development in their quest, Zatdatine and<br>
Kreeden, the unlikely pair of Half-Elf Bard and Iksar<br>
Necromancer, set off for the Karanas to discover<br>
what lay ahead for them in Kelethin--and what that<br>
mysterious light was...<br>
<br>
While zipping through the Western Plains of Karana with<br>
the aid of Zatdatine's rendition of Selo's Accelerando, a<br>
young Wood Elf, brown and green as the trees she served, came running toward them with the aid of the<br>
Spirit of Wolf.  Since she wore no chainmail, Zatdatine<br>
supposed she was a Druid as opposed to a Ranger. <br>
The Wood Elf's face, though pretty, was torn with panic<br>
and sorrow.  What in Norrath could be wrong? <br>
<br>
&quot;I am Leleli Leafrunner,&quot; said the Wood Elf, tears in her<br>
eyes.  &quot;I am a Druid in the service of the Soldiers of<br>
Tunare,&quot; she told Zatdatine.  Through her tears, she<br>
could see an enshrouded figure that she instinctively<br>
did not trust, so she addressed herself to the Half-Elf. <br>
&quot;Or, at least, I was until a few moments ago!  Innoruuk,<br>
the Prince of Hate, has sent his servants, the Orcs, <br>
to set explosive devices in every building in Kelethin <br>
and make our fair city blow up!&quot;  Leleli was frantic. <br>
<br>
Zatdatine felt like someone had just punched her in the<br>
stomach.  Kelethin?  Blown up?  Since when had Orcs<br>
gotten the upper hand in their perpetual battle against<br>
the good-hearted Fier'Dal?  The Bard's heart raced. <br>
<br>
&quot;What are you going to do?&quot; she asked the Druid.<br>
<br>
&quot;First of all,&quot; she said, &quot;I'm going to alert Surefall Glade<br>
and tell them what has happened.  Then I'll return to<br>
my despoiled homeland and slaughter every Orc in<br>
Crushbone until they're all dead!&quot;  Leleli's green eyes<br>
blazed with righteous anger.  &quot;And then, after that, <br>
my heart will finally be ready for the great battle against<br>
Innoruuk himself!  Veeshan, the Wurmqueen, wants to<br>
lead the charge, and Tunare has not told her nay!  <br>
Normally, we'd regard this supercilious serpent as a <br>
traitor and a haughty beast, but since we need all the<br>
help we can get to destroy Innoruuk, we regard Veeshan<br>
as an ally instead of a foe.  Will you help us fight?&quot; <br>
<br>
Zatdatine nodded her head up and down furiously.  &quot;I<br>
will help my mistress fight!&quot; she cried.  &quot;Veeshan shall<br>
triumph over the puny efforts of the Hateful One!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;And Tunare,&quot; scolded the Wood Elf, mindful that the<br>
Half-Elf was thinking only of serving her own deity.  <br>
Leleli looked toward the wrapped Iksar.  &quot;And what<br>
about your friend here?&quot; she asked rather disdainfully. <br>
&quot;Will he fight, or is he too much of a coward even to<br>
show his face?&quot;  She tried to look beyond the shroud. <br>
<br>
&quot;He's very sick,&quot; said the Bard.  &quot;I'm taking him to the<br>
High Elves to have him cured of leprosy.  Even Rodcet<br>
Nife, the Prime Healer, has not been able to cure this<br>
serious disease.  When he is well again, he will decide <br>
whether or not to join the battle against Innoruuk.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;See that he joins us,&quot; growled Leleli, &quot;or dies in his<br>
cowardice!  Meet us at the Karana spires when ye are<br>
ready to join forces with us, O Bard of Veeshan!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;And the leper,&quot; Zatdatine mentioned humbly. <br>
<br>
&quot;Oh, yes.  And the leper.  Farewell!&quot;  Leleli sped off. <br>
<br>
&quot;No matter what happens to me,&quot; whispered Zatdatine<br>
once the Wood Elf had gone, &quot;I would not deliver you<br>
into the hands of certain death!  The High Elves of <br>
Felwithe, the goodliest race of them all, would kill ye!<br>
That's why we'll avoid that pompous place and head--<br>
and head--!&quot;  Since Kelethin had exploded, where<br>
would they go next on their DragonQuest?<br>
<br>
&quot;Also,&quot; said Zatdatine, a concerned look in her eyes, <br>
&quot;I know that your master, Cazic-Thule, is an ally of<br>
Innoruuk, the Prince of Hate!  I must help my Mistress<br>
fight her dark foe, yet you might not want to.  Whatever you decide, I shall respect you all the more.  Vacht?&quot; <br>
She smiled.  &quot;Vacht&quot; was Half-Elvish for &quot;All right?&quot; <br>
<br>
She waited for the hidden Iksar's reply.      <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kreeden>Kreeden</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.badassbuddy.com/images/buddies/badassbuddy_com-hydros.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 12<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/19/03 9:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1008.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> You want ME to do what?</span><hr size=1> The iskar nodded thoughtfully.  &quot;This is a matter I have not given much thought to.  My alegion to a diety that is.  Sure, it is to Cazic-Thule that I devoted mindless hours of perfecting the art of sleeping with my eyes open in the chapel, however it is the closer 'appointments' of Cazic-Thule that deemed me to be an outcast.  I have no faith in such a belief in which cultural knowledge is frowned upon.&quot;  The iskar paused, collecting his thoughts.  <br>
<br>
Absentmindly, the iskar began walking towards the spires in the karanas.  He continued, &quot;My profession, is seemingly dependent upon worship of an 'evil' god.  However they, too, would shun my intentions of venturing Norrath, willingly or not.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;So, what are you suggesting?  Even if you declare to be neutral to the Feir'dal, you will still be handled mercilessly, for simply your skin alone.&quot;  Zatdatine said.<br>
<br>
&quot;I don't know...  but I believe I have a plan.  Innoruuk can very well know of me but he very well may not.  I'd doubt he has time to sit around and monitor the dealings of a hermit iskar.  I consider myself neutral, I only seek understanding.  Thusly, it is my belief that Innoruuks invasion must be stopped.  Leleli only mentioned Kelethin.  I'm assuming Felwhite is still holding out, but not for long.  I'd assume an alliance with Kaladim has been forged also.&quot;<br>
<br>
Zatdatine nodded agreeingly, eyes darting about out of thought.<br>
<br>
&quot;Maybe, I could act as a double agent of some sort...  It's a crazy idea, but truly, my stay here, among softskins will not be much longer, it is only time before I am sought out by a bounty hunter, framed for some un-committed crime.  Why not chance it...  though you may be in dubious standing with your current alligences with the elves, I ask of you to seek their headmaster, king, whatever title he is donned, and ask about me, grant me and my kind understanding in his city, and I will grant him intelligence of Innoruuk, and his buddies.&quot;<br>
<br>
Zatdatine's eyes got fairly wide, noticing the sucidial consequences of this proprosal.  Could she not only admit to dealing with an iskar to the high king of Felwhite,  but then beg for admittance to his own stronghold for her scaly friend and his brethern?  Kreeden's eyes narrowed as he looked seriously back to his comrade, the spires were near, the time to decide was now.  The destiny of Faydwer, and Norrath alike could depend on it. <p>&lt;center&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font color=&quot;red&quot;&gt; Kreeden - 60 Phantasmist Retired&lt;/font&gt;<br>
