silver-armored Paladin guards at the entrance<br>
neither smiled at her nor prepared to attack.  <br>
Instead, their expressions were a mixture of<br>
mistrust and sorrow.  They must have sensed<br>
intuitively that a Bard of Veeshan--and a half-<br>
breed, no less!--was headed into their fair city,<br>
the fairest of all cities now, for who knew what<br>
purpose!  They hoped she was not on Hate's side.<br>
<br>
She headed straight for the center of the gleaming,<br>
white High Elven city, looking for anyone who might<br>
know the way to the King's palace.  Shortly, she<br>
came upon a strolling Paladin, Sentry Mithriladil,<br>
who looked at her with an expression of helpful<br>
curiosity.  &quot;May I help you, milady?&quot; he asked. <br>
<br>
&quot;Yes.  I'm looking for the King of Felwithe,&quot; she said<br>
meekly, &quot;and I would be much obliged if you would<br>
let me speak to him right now.&quot;  Her eyes were full<br>
of sincerity, which the Paladin did not miss.  Mithriladil<br>
nodded purposefully and led her off toward the castle. <br>
<br>
Inside, the Clerics of Tunare all surrounded their <br>
monarch, protecting him with holy spells and assuring<br>
him that within these walls, nothing could harm him. <br>
Neither the Orcs' fury nor Innoruuk's hate would enter<br>
here, they said, for Tunare herself was guarding them.<br>
<br>
&quot;Excuse me,&quot; said Mithriladil.  &quot;This young lady wants<br>
to speak to you.&quot;  The green-robed King (favored as the<br>
royal color of the Mother of All instead of that pretentious<br>
purple), pursed his lips and ordered Zatdatine, &quot;Speak!&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;I am Zatdatine,&quot; she began, kneeling on the ground before the King, &quot;of the League of Antonican Bards.  I<br>
am a Half-Elf, milord, so you can imagine the great<br>
pain I felt when I first heard of Kelethin's destruction!  <br>
I've travelled here all the way from the distant city of<br>
Qeynos, both by foot and by spires, and I've brought<br>
a friend.  Both of us wish to help you fight Innoruuk.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Excellent,&quot; said the King.  &quot;Where is your friend now?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Outside the city,&quot; said the Bard, &quot;waiting on a nearby<br>
hill.  I must tell you, milord, that due to his race, he<br>
is not well-accepted within your magnificent city, Sire!&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;When does a Half-Elf hang around with a Dark one?&quot; the<br>
King growled.  &quot;Hang ye high, you young witch!  Do you<br>
seek to destroy us by bringing this 'friend' of yours into<br>
our midst?!  All of the good races of Norrath are duly accepted in Felwithe, even the simple-minded Dwarves! <br>
If this companion of yours is not tolerated here, then he<br>
must be one of the Evil races--Ogre, Troll, Dark Elf, or<br>
the worst of all--the wicked Iksar!  Which one is he, <br>
wench?&quot;  The Clerics of Tunare raised their maces high.<br>
<br>
&quot;He's an Iksar,&quot; replied Zatdatine, prostrating herself flat and face-down on the ground humbly.  &quot;He wants to fight, merciful King, so let him take up arms against<br>
Innoruuk!  The Iksar of which I speak is a Necromancer,<br>
yet he's been exiled and wishes to gain faction with<br>
this fine town!&quot;  She dared not raise her eyes upward. <br>
<br>
The King, abhorring all things Iksar, turned to the<br>
Clerics.  &quot;Mind ye go out and slay this beast, or all <br>
your faithless and treasonous Elven heads shall roll!&quot;  <br>
<br>
&quot;No!&quot;  Zatdatine screamed.  &quot;If you kill him, I'll die, too!&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Don't harm yourself over slime, milady,&quot; said the King,<br>
&quot;for he, that Iksar you speak of, would rather turn you<br>
into one of his skeleton pets than to help you truly!&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Not so!&quot; the Bard cried.  &quot;I yield me to you, and all <br>
my service to Veeshan, so long as you give this one<br>
a chance!&quot;  The King was taken by her fierce devotion. <br>
<br>
&quot;I'll test this one,&quot; said the King, and he called for some<br>
parchment to write a note.  In the brownish-green ink of<br>
the Koada'Dal, he wrote, &quot;Iksar:  Commit yourself to<br>
Crushbone, and hide in the caves until some Orcs<br>
start talking of their latest plans.  Tell your Bard here<br>
the battle reports, and then I shall let you into our city.<br>
Signed, His Majesty, King Tearis Thex of Felwithe.&quot; <br>
<br>
He would not let Zatdatine deliver the letter.  Instead, <br>
he called for one of his Clerics to place the document<br>
in a lowly forest drakeling's mouth, which soon reached<br>
Kreeden.  Reading the letter, his resolve strengthened,<br>
yet he wondered whether he should not go elsewhere.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kreeden>Kreeden</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.badassbuddy.com/images/buddies/badassbuddy_com-hydros.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 14<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/20/03 10:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1008.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Hello Crushbone.  Bye Crushbone.</span><hr size=1> (ooc: wow, this is way to long, however I won't be able to post tomorrow (Saturday) so I'll post next Sunday.  Apologize for this being so long but I didn't want to condense it and make it so simple :P )<br>
<br>
<br>
Kreeden hurried, yet stepping carefully, towards Crushbone.    He knew not the exact location of it, and dared not follow the common paths, however heading towards the sounds of the cycles of battle seemed good enough.  <br>
<br>
Kreeden eventually came into the sight of a small orc, likely a pawn, who seemed to be scouting the area.  Kreeden dared to uncloak himself in the clear view of this young orc.  The orc seemed very ready to throw himself to death at the iskar's feet, however kept his distance.  &quot;I am Kreeden.  I am here to see Innoruuk, or Emperor Crush, possibly even Ambassador D'Vinn.  It would be much appreciated by myself and advantageous to you to guide me to your superiors.&quot;<br>
<br>
The orc pondered things for a moment, and likely fearing the iksar would kill him if he didn't oblige, he lead Kreeden in a straight line to the entrance of Crushbone.  The outside was well fortified, powerful orc legionaries manned a line in front of rather intimidating goblin spellcasters.  No being seemed to pay attention to Kreeden, which was a good thing.  Suddenly a very bad thought came to Kreeden's mind.  The letter from the High King was still stowed in his backpack.  He had meant to destroy it, however it was to late for that now.  They would surely search his belongings.  <br>
<br>
Kreeden considered placing the letter in a passing orc's pocket, however the letter itself was addressed &quot;Dear Iksar:&quot;  No, that would not work.  Passing through the short cavern that is the entrance to Crushbone, Kreeden saw a large torch, perfect..  Kreeden all in one fluid motion reached into his pack, which was shifted to his side, and placed the note carefully into the fire.  The note burned a bright green for just a moment, and then it was gone.  The Orc led him around an eastward wall, and up to a shabby looking castle.  &quot;Orcs are ones for hospitality&quot;  Kreeden mused to himself. <br>
<br>
The pawn left Kreeden at the steps, and Kreeden thanked him and walked up the stairs, opening the two large doors and walking in. <br>
<br>
The castle itself was as shabby on the interior as the exterior.  You'd think that if Innoruuk was taking over Crushbone, he'd at least add a nice palace to accompany him and make himself feel at home.  There was no hallways, just one straight corridor, a few steps, an incline, and a right turn and he was in what appeared to be a conference hall of some sort, a throne was the central feature, with benches in front of it, and a large table in the back, closet to Kreeden.<br>
<br>
A large orc was sitting on the throne, in a hunched over position.  He whispered something to a nearby oracle, who nodded and disappeared behind the throne.  Kreeden stood for a moment, uncertain of where to move or what to say, he hadn't thought this far ahead, getting rid of the hot note was enough stress.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yessss,&quot;  Kreeden said at last, making sure to stress his s's, as a normal iksar would, one who hasn't been 'tainted' by relating with softskins, &quot;I am Kreeden, an iksssar on a field missssssion for my guild in Cabilisss.&quot;<br>
<br>
The orc nodded, beckoning him to continue.<br>
<br>
&quot;I have heard of the fight againssssst ssssoft sssskinss here, and wissssh to ally myssself with you...&quot;<br>
<br>
The orc held a hand outward, palm facing Kreeden, and shifted a little bit to peer behind the throne.  A  medium build dark elf appeared from behind the throne, dressed in chain mail and wielding a small dagger and a short sword.  &quot;Yes, what have we here, Crush?&quot;<br>
<br>
Kreeden assumed the orc was adressed as 'Crush', and made mental note of that.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ambassador, Dis lizard say he want fight softies.&quot;  Crush's grammar was bad, but not as bad as those horrendous ogres.<br>
<br>
The dark-elf replied, &quot;Well let's see what our friend is made of.. word has it that the oh-so-high-and-mighty Feir'Dal, or as I like to say, INfeirOR'Dal&quot; here the dark elf laughed at his own joke, joined in a chorus by the orcs and Kreeden, &quot;are planning another full frontal assualt.  Let's send our friend to the front lines.&quot;<br>
<br>
Crush nodded, and the same oracle that had fetched the dark elf grabbed Kreeden by the arm and led him back out of the fortress, back to the entrance of Crushbone.  Here Kreeden sat on the steep slope, watching the orcs and goblins talking and trading, some sleeping.  A battle horn sounded and instantly everyone wheeled around in the direction of the sound.  Sure enough, it was a full frontal assualt.  First, two mages on horseback charged up the steep mound, casting while riding, one fell to two arrows from some orc archers, however the second, a young male, directed a fireball to the right wing of the orcs, it devastated many, Kreeden was positioned in the center however, but his intelligence told him something was up.  Kreeden moved to the left wing, attempting to avoid death, giving or recieving, at all costs.  Within seconds of the fireball, the mage fell to a chorus of spells from the goblins, who cheered at their smiting.  Their grins faded as at least twenty paladins on horseback and numerous rangers wielding shimmering swords and whips began charging up the mound.  The battle was intense, and Kreeden did kill many, as the dark elf whom had talked to him in the castle had come down and joined the fighting.  He knew he was being watched and he knew the purpose he was here was worth far more then the few lives Kreeden ended with his dark magics.  But yet, the senseless killing made a knot in Kreeden's stomach.  <br>
<br>
The battle was over, and Crushbone won, largely due to the magics of the high level goblin wizards, and the assistance of the Ambassador, whom Kreeden did not know.  The lines were dismissed with a new shift, so they may get rested back within the stronghold.  Kreeden followed them but the Ambassador pulled him aside.<br>
<br>
&quot;I was watching you...&quot; the Ambassador began, &quot;you're pretty good.  We might have use for you yet.  Come up to my quarters in the castle tonight, when the moon is fresh.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kreeden nodded, his open wounds from battle were almost healed already, only two, one from the blade of a ranger and the other from the kickback of a spell he fired at the fore-mentioned ranger.  <br>
<br>
Kreeden familiarized himself with the fortress, incase the King would need such information, which was doubted yet helpful nonetheless.  Kreeden was unable to sleep, so occupied himself swimming in the canal system.  He found it more appealing then walking, and soothing to be alone and contemplate things.  Kreeden thought of his home, Zatdatine, the stakes being so high, and all depending upon him, since Zatdatine had done her part.  Yes, the stakes were so high as to say that the destiny of Norrath depended on this, and here was the hero, floating on his back in a canal in Crushbone.  He wished for Zatdatine's safety, knowning that her message had been delivered but not knowing of her condition.  Kreeden momentairly lapsed into a napping state, and awoke when his head came into contact with a ladder leading out of the water.  <br>
<br>
It was nighttime, and it seemed well enough to go back into the fortress, and proceed into the room he was in before, and meet the Ambassador behind the throne.  Kreeden did just that, and upon meeting the Ambassador, the Ambassador dismissed his servant orcs and offered Kreeden to sit.<br>
<br>
Kreeden's tail didn't allow for easily sitting, however he managed as the Ambassador spoke.<br>
<br>
&quot;I am Ambassador D'Vinn..  I am here as the material force of Innoruuk, whom has moved this assualt into action.  We aim to conquer Faydwer, and then extend the regime to Neriak by way of Freeport, and to expand in all directions from that.  We will conquer Norrath, however we're confronting obstacles early.  The Feir'Dal are quickly wearing out the simple minded orcs and goblins we have as hired help until Innoruuk can organize his minions in the Plane of Hate, to come through a portal and attack.  We need to plant false information into the hands of the Feir'Dal.  They no doubt assume our full assualt will come from this stronghold.  While in fact, our blessed Innoruuk has devised a way to summon his minions from the spires in Faydark.  A brilliant plan, really, to feed the Feir'Dal information, the correct date and time of the assualt, however the wrong location.  If we accomplish this, the Feir'dal will protect the wrong side of their defense, Innoruuk's minions will overrun and slaughter them, while we sit back and drink fine mead and prepare for Kaladim.&quot;<br>
<br>
D'Vinn paused here, and Kreeden broke the silence.<br>
<br>
&quot;Brilliant, however where do I come into play?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Well, you'll give them the false information.  You see, if an orc or goblin, or even Teir'dal were captured, we would be killed just as quickly as the hundreds of others they have.  However, an iksar in these parts is rare, and they would likely interrogate you, believing that you held a high rank or were an ambassador of some sort.  Don't give the information quickly, however give it piece by piece.  The attack will be in ten days... when the moon is high.  Go now, become captured, and plant this information.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kreeden nodded, shocked that D'Vinn expected him to blindly walk into Felwithe, become captured and tortured.  Wow.<br>
<br>
&quot;I know you may be a bit apprehensive of walking into death for the greater good of things, however just remember, an entire regime of evil will rule because of YOUR sacrifice.  My legionairres will show you out and make you look fit to capture.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Fit to capture?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Well, you have to look a little beat up.. this will only take a second...&quot;  A blunt object hit the back of Kreeden's head and he crumpled to the ground in a heap.  Everything faded to black.<br>
<br>
When Kreeden awoke, he squinted through his sore eyes, between bars, and into the concerned and stressed eyes of a high elf in a green-robe.  What had happened in the time Kreeden was out was of no memory to him.<br>
